        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-12-14 13:47:51.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1\n\n(5 comments)",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "e8cc3b02919939a2c8add9b9a03e61f0f0199b74",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-12-14 14:34:41.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nJim, what's the reason for the swapping of arguments Assert.assertEquals()? \n\nIt makes sense with the String.equals comparison, as you want to preceded it with the constant to prevent passing null pointers, but this is not that case, and it is instead a method call into the Junit Assert class, rather than String comparison, and the same concern does not apply.   If you look into the Junit library, it does a Strings.valueOf on each argument and then it compares, so will never run into that kind of situation.\n\nI guess, I would like to understand what's the rule or rationale dictating argument order into arbitrary method calls into 3rd party libraries, as it is an arbitrary method call to a 3rd party method that takes 2 strings, and not a String.equals comparison.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "8296c1fed04f05aa561846ac1073de9e0146883d",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-12-14 15:55:46.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nIt shows me 88.2% and 70% line coverage respectively for each class.   This is the report I get:\n\n[ all classes ] [ org.onap.policy.drools.apps.controlloop.feature.management ]\nCoverage Summary for Package: org.onap.policy.drools.apps.controlloop.feature.management\nPackage \tClass, % \tMethod, % \tLine, %\norg.onap.policy.drools.apps.controlloop.feature.management \t100% (1/ 1) \t100% (5/ 5) \t88.2% (15/ 17)\n\n\nClass \tClass, % \tMethod, % \tLine, %\nControlLoopManagementFeature \t100% (1/ 1) \t100% (5/ 5) \t88.2% (15/ 17)\ngenerated on 2018-12-14 09:49\n\n\n[ all classes ] [ org.onap.policy.drools.server.restful ]\nCoverage Summary for Package: org.onap.policy.drools.server.restful\nPackage \tClass, % \tMethod, % \tLine, %\norg.onap.policy.drools.server.restful \t100% (1/ 1) \t100% (5/ 5) \t70% (35/ 50)\n\n\nClass \tClass, % \tMethod, % \tLine, %\nRestControlLoopManager \t100% (1/ 1) \t100% (5/ 5) \t70% (35/ 50)\ngenerated on 2018-12-14 09:49\n\nI can try to bump up the 70% class one in future reviews.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "53b0684ea6300583c4ae90c1e16a660acf849825",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-12-16 14:47:42.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> Jim, what's the reason for the swapping of arguments\n > Assert.assertEquals()?\n > \n > It makes sense with the String.equals comparison, as you want to\n > preceded it with the constant to prevent passing null pointers, but\n > this is not that case, and it is instead a method call into the\n > Junit Assert class, rather than String comparison, and the same\n > concern does not apply.   If you look into the Junit library, it\n > does a Strings.valueOf on each argument and then it compares, so\n > will never run into that kind of situation.\n > \n > I guess, I would like to understand what's the rule or rationale\n > dictating argument order into arbitrary method calls into 3rd party\n > libraries, as it is an arbitrary method call to a 3rd party method\n > that takes 2 strings, and not a String.equals comparison.\n\nThe semantics are: assertEquals(expected, actual).  Junit error messages assume this order.  However, there are other reasons to follow this order, including technical reasons with which I was unaware, listed in this link:\nhttps://stackoverflow.com/questions/16267660/assert-assertequals-junit-parameters-order",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
